&lt;h4 id=&#34;cluster-estimated-standard-errors-in-r-ceserpublicationferrari-2019-ceser&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://DiogoFerrari.github.io/publication/ferrari-2019-ceser/&#34;&gt;Cluster Estimated Standard Errors in R (ceser)&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;table&gt;
&lt;thead&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;th&gt;&lt;/th&gt;
&lt;th&gt;&lt;/th&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/thead&gt;
&lt;tbody&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;https://DiogoFerrari.github.io/img/ceser_logo.png&#34; align=&#34;left&#34; width=&#34;600&#34; style=&#34;padding-right: 20px;&#34;&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;div align=&#34;justify&#34;&gt;(with &lt;a href=&#34;https://lsa.umich.edu/polisci/people/emeriti/jjacksn.html&#34;&gt;John Jackson&lt;/a&gt;) The package implements the Cluster Estimated Standard Errors (CESE) method proposed by Jackson (2019) to compute clustered standard errors of linear coefficients in regression models with grouped data. CESE produces more conservative confidence intervals, outperform the classical clustered robust standard error (CRSE) method in various ways, and avoid CRSE downward bias and underestimation of the clustered standard errors. (see Jackson, J., (2019) &lt;a href=&#34;https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/political-analysis/article/corrected-standard-errors-with-clustered-data/F2332E494290725256181955B9BC7428&#34;&gt;Corrected standard errors with clustered data&lt;/a&gt;, Political Analysis)&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
